# Terminal easy tier tasks — 10 tasks
# Format: task_name|prompt
# Tests: basic terminal + coding workflow skills (debugging with CLI, reading errors, patching files, using git/grep/go tools)
# Each task provides BROKEN code inline. The agent writes it, fixes it, and verifies with a specific command.

fix-failing-test|Work in /tmp/training-fix-failing-test/. Run: mkdir -p /tmp/training-fix-failing-test && cd /tmp/training-fix-failing-test && go mod init training/fix-failing-test. Write math.go in package main: func Double(n int) int { return n * 3 }. Write math_test.go: package main; import "testing"; func TestDouble(t *testing.T) { cases := []struct{ in, want int }{{0,0},{1,2},{5,10},{-3,-6}}; for _, c := range cases { if got := Double(c.in); got != c.want { t.Errorf("Double(%d)=%d want %d", c.in, got, c.want) } } }. Run go test ./... — it will fail. Fix the bug in math.go (wrong multiplier). Run go test ./... again to verify. Report the final test output.

grep-and-patch|Work in /tmp/training-grep-patch/. Run: mkdir -p /tmp/training-grep-patch && cd /tmp/training-grep-patch && go mod init training/grep-patch. Write three files. config.go: package main; const DefaultPort = "8080"; const DefaultHost = "localhoost". server.go: package main; import "fmt"; func Addr() string { return DefaultHost + ":" + DefaultPort }. server_test.go: package main; import "testing"; func TestAddr(t *testing.T) { if got := Addr(); got != "localhost:8080" { t.Errorf("got %q", got) } }. Use grep to find the typo: run grep -n "localhoost" *.go. Fix the typo in config.go. Run go test ./... to verify. Report the grep output and final test result.

nil-pointer-fix|Work in /tmp/training-nilfix/. Run: mkdir -p /tmp/training-nilfix && cd /tmp/training-nilfix && go mod init training/nilfix. Write user.go: package main; type User struct { Name string }; func GetName(u *User) string { return u.Name }. Write main_test.go: package main; import "testing"; func TestGetName(t *testing.T) { got := GetName(nil); if got != "" { t.Errorf("want empty, got %q", got) } }. Run go test ./... — it will panic with a nil pointer dereference. Fix GetName to guard against nil (if u == nil, return ""). Run go test ./... to confirm it passes. Report the stack trace you saw and the final passing output.

build-error-fix|Work in /tmp/training-build-fix/. Run: mkdir -p /tmp/training-build-fix && cd /tmp/training-build-fix && go mod init training/build-fix. Write calc.go: package main; func Add(a, b int) int { return a + b }; func Sub(a b int) int { return a - b }. Run go build ./... — it will fail with a syntax error. Read the compiler error carefully. Fix the missing comma in the Sub signature. Run go build ./... to confirm it compiles. Then write calc_test.go: package main; import "testing"; func TestSub(t *testing.T) { if Sub(5,3) != 2 { t.Fatal("wrong") } }. Run go test ./... and report the output.

git-blame-fix|Work in /tmp/training-git-blame/. Run: mkdir -p /tmp/training-git-blame && cd /tmp/training-git-blame && git init && go mod init training/git-blame. Write counter.go: package main; func Count(s []string) int { return len(s) + 1 }. Commit: git add -A && git commit -m "initial". Now write counter_test.go: package main; import "testing"; func TestCount(t *testing.T) { if Count([]string{"a","b"}) != 2 { t.Fatalf("got %d", Count([]string{"a","b"})) } }. Run go test ./... — fails. Use git log to see the commit history. Fix the off-by-one in counter.go (remove the +1). Run go test ./... to confirm it passes. Report the git log output and test result.

makefile-fix|Work in /tmp/training-makefile/. Run: mkdir -p /tmp/training-makefile && cd /tmp/training-makefile && go mod init training/makefile. Write hello.go: package main; import "fmt"; func main() { fmt.Println("hello") }. Write this Makefile (use real tabs, not spaces): Makefile with targets: all: build; build: go build -o bin/hello ./...; test: go test ./...; clean: rm -rf bin. The build target is broken because the bin/ directory does not exist. Fix the Makefile build target to create the bin/ directory first (add mkdir -p bin before the go build line). Run make build, then run make test. Report the output of both commands.

count-todos|Work in /tmp/training-todos/. Run: mkdir -p /tmp/training-todos && cd /tmp/training-todos && go mod init training/todos. Write three files with TODO comments. a.go: package main; // TODO: implement retry logic; func Retry() {}; // TODO: add tests. b.go: package main; func Handle() {}; // TODO: handle errors here. c.go: package main; // TODO: remove debug logging; func Debug() {}. Use grep -rn "TODO" . to find all TODOs. Count the total number by piping to wc -l: grep -c "TODO" *.go gives per-file counts. Use grep -rh "TODO" . | wc -l for the total. Report the exact command you ran and the total count (should be 4).

parse-log-errors|Work in /tmp/training-logscan/. Run: mkdir -p /tmp/training-logscan && cd /tmp/training-logscan. Write app.log with these lines (one per line using printf or a heredoc): ERROR db_connect failed; INFO server started; ERROR timeout on request; ERROR db_connect failed; INFO health ok; ERROR auth_failed; ERROR db_connect failed; INFO cleanup done; ERROR timeout on request; ERROR db_connect failed. Use grep and sort and uniq -c to find the most frequent error line. Command: grep "^ERROR" app.log | sort | uniq -c | sort -rn | head -1. Report the command and output showing db_connect failed appears 4 times.

govet-fix|Work in /tmp/training-govet/. Run: mkdir -p /tmp/training-govet && cd /tmp/training-govet && go mod init training/govet. Write vet.go: package main; import "fmt"; func main() { var x int = 42; fmt.Sprintf("value: %d", x); s := "unused variable below"; _ = s; fmt.Printf("done\n") }. The fmt.Sprintf result is discarded — go vet will flag this. Run go vet ./... to see the warning. Fix vet.go by changing fmt.Sprintf to fmt.Printf so the output actually prints. Run go vet ./... again to confirm it is clean, then run go build ./... to confirm it compiles. Report both vet outputs (before and after fix).

gomod-fix|Work in /tmp/training-gomod/. Run: mkdir -p /tmp/training-gomod && cd /tmp/training-gomod. Write go.mod with wrong module path: module wrongpath/myapp; go 1.21. Write main.go: package main; import "fmt"; func main() { fmt.Println("ok") }. Run go build ./... — it will succeed but the module path is wrong. Now write main_test.go: package main; import "testing"; func TestMain2(t *testing.T) { t.Log("ok") }. Run go test ./... to verify it works. Now fix go.mod: change the module line to: module training/gomod. Run go test ./... again to confirm tests still pass with the corrected module path. Report both test outputs showing before and after.
